\pard\f0\fs28  The European plant belongs to subsp.{\b  oligantha} (Turcz.) Hultén, {\i Lunds Univ. Årsskr.} nov. ser., {\b 39}({\b 1}): 481 (1943) ({\i P. oligantha} Turcz., {\i Lysiella oligantha} (Turcz.) Nevski), which is also found in E. Siberia. Subsp.{\i  obtusata}, which is confined to America, has an obovate leaf, a laxer spike, a longer, narrower labellum and a longer spur. Plants from E. North America are very distinct from those from Europe and Asia, but intermediates are found in Alaska.
